\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6448152 WB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid656999\charrsid7276462 No. No. Honey. Honey. Not sulphur. Paregoric. Paregoric. That's
 what you got at the chemist and you'd have to cart this basin around and then - when you got home it'd be mixed up and stood on the hob, you know, of course those old fashioned fires, oven one side and a - boiler the other you know. That was before the -
 before you had - cookers on feet, anything like that, because there was no gas cookers then. Gas rings, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9141532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid656999\charrsid7276462 She'd mix it up on the cooker then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6448152 WB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid656999\charrsid7276462 
She'd - oh yes, she'd mix it up and - and it had to stand goodness knows how long and then it'd be - then it'd be put into - bottles, you know, and you'd have to have a spoonful or - in the morning and at night for a cough or a cold or something.
